{"annotations": [{"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997797608375549, "span": {"begin": 0, "end": 9}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986221790313721, "span": {"begin": 89, "end": 98}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994480013847351, "span": {"begin": 107, "end": 115}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "estrogen receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9943131804466248, "span": {"begin": 107, "end": 125}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9991154074668884, "span": {"begin": 127, "end": 129}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "downstream", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6995059251785278, "span": {"begin": 173, "end": 183}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen-responsive genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8821046352386475, "span": {"begin": 184, "end": 209}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9892174005508423, "span": {"begin": 184, "end": 192}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9982417821884155, "span": {"begin": 343, "end": 352}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "&beta;-estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993165135383606, "span": {"begin": 356, "end": 372}}], "text": "Estrogens are essential for normal ovarian differentiation, growth and maintenance. When estrogens bind to estrogen receptors (ER), these then regulate the transcription of downstream estrogen-responsive genes necessary for proper gonad development&nbsp;(Guiguen et al.&nbsp;2010; Gorelick et al.&nbsp;2011).&nbsp;Among the different forms of estrogens, 17&beta;-estradiol (E2) is considered the most fundamental in gonad differentiation in most vertebrates, as it is responsible for inducing and maintaining ovarian development (Bondesson et al.&nbsp;2015; Li et al.&nbsp;2019). Consequently, disruption of the E2 synthesis by the undifferentiated gonad has been linked to altered gonad differentiation and development in many vertebrates.&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:50:32 +0000 2026"}